<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-256-190  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 256 190.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  Feb 14 1990 n126 p135(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PC Power Protection (Read Only)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rake, Katherine.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BooksReviewPower SupplyPC Power Protection (Book).andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   User verdict. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>PC Power ProtectionandM;When is an uninterruptible power system not an uninterruptible power system?andO;-- when it it's a standby power system, according to Mark Waller in PC PowerProtection.andM;Waller takes a detailed look at how to protect your PC against power supplydisturbances, starting with an explanation of how electricity and the powersupply works.andP;  His main aim is to allow users to understand the causes ofpower supply disturbances and to be able to identify those most likely tooccur on their PCs or system.andM;For example, Waller explains that most power supplies are dirty; that is,there are various amounts of potential power disturbance in the electricitysupply.andP;  Some PCs are more susceptible to one type of disturbance, such as adrop in current, than others.andP;  The duration and magnitude of a supplydisturbance is another factor which has to be taken into account.andP;  Wallerruns through a list of disturbances which can be expected, such as surges,impulses and sags.andM;Waller advises users on the most appropriate technology to use to protecttheir particular systems.andP;  With standby power systems, such as batteries,Waller explains how they only act as backups -- going into action only oncethe power supply has gone down.andM;The book is very detailed and at times highly complicated.andP;  I'd advisereaders to take a note of the pros and cons of the various solutions thatWaller offers -- and to make sure that you know your own system well.andP;  Alsonote that he's talking about US electricity supplies as far as voltages areconcerned.andO;</TEXT></DOC>